{"id":"quant-ph/0207054","submitter":"Afshin Shafiee","authors":"Afshin Shafiee, Mehdi Golshani and M. Ghasem Mahjani","title":"Bell's Theorem and Chemical Potential","comments":"11 pages,1 figure, To appear in J. Phy. A: Math. Gen., Special Issue:\n  Foundations of Quantum Theory","journal-ref":"J. Phy. A: Math. Gen. 35 (2002) 8627-8634","doi":"10.1088/0305-4470/35/40/319","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Chemical potential is a property which involves the effect of interaction\nbetween the components of a system, and it results from the whole system. In\nthis paper, we argue that for two particles which have interacted via their\nspins and are now spatially separated, the so-called Bell's locality condition\nimplies that the chemical potential of each particle is an individual property.\nHere is a point where quantum statistical mechanics and the local hidden\nvariable theories are in conflict. Based on two distinct concepts of chemical\npotential, the two theories predict two different patterns for the energy\nlevels of a system of two entangled particles. In this manner, we show how one\ncan distinguish the non-separable features of a two-particle system.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 10 Jul 2002 08:51:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
